<p class="mgSubItemTitleTxt">Minutes:</p>
<div class="mgWordPara"><div class="WordSection1">
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The Corporate Director
of Resources presented the report, it was noted that this was a
regular report and additional actions had been included compared
with previous reports. The report set out the latest position.
Members were advised that as this Committee meeting was taking
place prior to the two February Cabinet meetings a fuller version
would be presented to the Committee in March 2026. A budget report
would be considered by Cabinet on 02 February 2025, which would
provide the Council&rsquo;s final savings proposals, along with
2025-2026 Financial Performance Report for Quarter three. The full
budget for 2026-27 and the treasury management strategy, the
capital strategy and programme, the Housing Revenue Account and
Dedicated Schools grant was due at Cabinet on 23 February
2026.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">In response to
Members&rsquo; questions, it was explained that:</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">&nbsp;</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0cm">
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Identifying further
savings over and above those already identified in demand led
services was challenging;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Discretionary
spending was under continuous review and could be reprofiled as
required;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The threshold for
spend control panel approval would be reduced from &pound;10,000 to
&pound;5,000;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Full Council would
receive a budget report that would set out the capital strategy and
strategic asset management framework. This would explain how the
council manage assets and would include the asset disposal
policy;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The Council was
developing a Housing Revenue Account (HRA) financial recovery plan,
details of which would be added to the action plan;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The property market
remained challenging; however, Cabinet had approved the
commencement of the HRA disposals;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Two tranches of HRA
disposals had already been completed, with properties achieving or
exceeding market value;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The most recent HRA
disposal tranche was estimated to generate &pound;10-&pound;11m
income;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span class="SpellE"><span style=
"">Forvis</span></span><span style="">-Mazars had completed
extensive work on leaseholder charge objections, but further
discussions with the Council were required to determine their
impact;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Statutory
recommendation four was related to Homes for Lambeth (<span class=
"SpellE">HfL</span>), not the HRA.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Other recommendations
highlighting financial resilience and reserves applied to both the
HRA and General Fund;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Recommendation two
had a significant target; directorates had developed business cases
and undergone challenge sessions to provide detailed savings
information;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Directorates had been
asked to complete savings delivery plans, implications, and
timelines for achieving their savings;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Projects not yet in
contract, not fully externally funded or were not related to safety
critical compliance spend had been paused whilst a review of the
capital programme was completed;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Cabinet Members
regularly reviewed the paused capital programme, and projects
affecting savings delivery were only paused where borrowing costs
outweighed capital savings;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Paused projects would
now be reviewed to identify invest-to-save opportunities without
