<p class="mgSubItemTitleTxt">Minutes:</p>
<div class="mgWordPara"><div class="WordSection1">
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The report was
introduced by the Director of Resources, who shared that it comes
annually to the Committee, and that the Council was required to set
the Council Tax base before 31 March 2026. It was explained that
the Council Tax base was determined by the number of dwellings
adjusted to the Council Tax band which the Council was able to
charge Council Tax for. This in turn helped form a calculation of
Council Tax income which would form part of the budget report that
would go to Full Council. The Committee were advised that the NNDR1
forms would become available after the date of the meeting and the
Corporate Director of Resources would need to finalise and approve
the NNDR1 form setting out the business rate tax base.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">In response to
Member&rsquo;s questions, it was explained that:</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">&nbsp;</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0cm">
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The decrease in the
Council Tax Base from 2025/6 to 2026/7 relied on a variety of
factors, such as the number of empty properties in the borough, and
that the accuracy of the estimates relied on many
variables.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The Council Tax Base
and its income calculation had been factored into the Medium-Term
Financial Strategy (MTFS).</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">That there were two
percentage statistics regarding Council Tax collection rates in the
report: actual and eventual, with the eventual rate being
96.5%.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The collection rate
was higher than it had been previously.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Reasons for the
higher collection rate included several variables, such as payment
plans, as well as a greater focus by the finance team to increase
collection rates.</span></li>
</ul>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="font-weight: bold"><span style=
"">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style=
"">RESOLVED</span></b><span style="">: That the Committee
unanimously:</span></p>
<ol start="1" style="margin-top:0cm">
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Approved the
calculation and the amount calculated as the Council Tax base for
the year 2026/27 at 116,594 (118,324 in 2025/26) as set out in
appendix 1(b).</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Approved the schedule
of discounts and premiums in paragraph 2.14.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Note the proposed
changes to the Council Tax Support Scheme (CTS) have been assumed
for planning purposes in setting the tax base. Should a decision be
taken not to proceed with the proposed changes to CTS scheme this
would be addressed in the calculation of the taxbase for 2027/28
and the shortfall would be reflected in updated Medium Term
Financial Strategy (MTFS) calculations.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Delegated authority
to the Corporate Director of Resources and S151 Officer to finalise
and approve the NNDR1 form setting out the business rate tax
base.</span></li>
</ol>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
