<p class="mgSubItemTitleTxt">Minutes:</p>
<div class="mgWordPara"><div class="WordSection1">
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">The report was introduced by
the Assistant Director of Procurement and Contract management, who
stated that the report summarised concerns from the Committee
meeting held on 25 November 2026 regarding purchasing compliance,
contract management, and social values. Within the report, an
action plan was presented alongside actions management have taken
to address those concerns and drive improvements in
compliance.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">In response to Member&rsquo;s
questions, it was explained that:</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">&nbsp;</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0cm">
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Breakdowns were made
by service area regarding non-compliance with purchase order
procedures, and these were provided on a quarterly basis and shared
with Directorates.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Improvements in the
level of compliance across different service areas have been made.
The Corporate Director for Resources confirmed that a fuller update
could be brought to the Committee meeting in March
2026.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Contract management
is decentralised across the Council, and compliance accountability
was handled by Directorates.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">There was
understanding among the Directorates that formal actions would be
taken where there was consistent noncompliance, and there have been
improvements in the process with the message that compliance should
be 100%.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">That management was
taking non-compliance within purchase order procedures
seriously.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Spend control is
entwined with the procurement process and that the threshold has
been lowered from &pound;10K to &pound;5K, with issues like
retrospective purchase orders being more easily
identified.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The culture around
compliance with procurement procedure rules needs to be changed to
improve compliance rates.</span></li>
</ul>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">It was noted that the Committee
wanted to see continued updates on this and could agree on full
reassurance when this comes back, with the Chair stating they did
not feel assured by the report, nor by current purchase order
non-compliance. Members shared concerns that it was too early to
tell that compliance efforts were a success and that while work was
being done, the proof would be in the results which required a
change in work culture as well as the efforts of the Procurement
team.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><b><span style=
"">RESOLVED</span></b><span style="">: Corporate Committee agreed
to consider assurance from the actions being taken to significantly
improve performance as set out in paragraphs 2.16 to 2.23 2 and
agreed to receive progress updates on the actions as part of future
procurement update reports.</span></p>
</div>
</div> 
					
